 It is a well-known fact that the mercury contamination affects both ecosystem
 and human health.
 Mercury pollution stem from both sources – natural and anthropogenic, where
 after its release into the environment mercury undergoes various (physical
 and chemical, often redox-related changes).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Driscoll2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Mercury poisoning results as a consequence of exposure to mercury, the
 severity of the poisoning, as usual, is dependent on the dose and the length
 of the exposure.
 Another factor that impacts the poisoning severity is the form of the mercury
 – various mercury forms are characterized by diverse absorbability and
 reactivity towards biological targets, e.g.
 methylmercury cation 
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Methylmercury cation is a major source of mercury poisoning in human.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cytacja
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 is easily absorbed into brain, liver, kidneys etc., while Hg(II) for various
 reasons, including the reactions with sulfhydryl groups on erythrocytes
 or glutathione in the plasma 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Clarkson TW, Gatzy J, Dalton E.
 UR-582.
 Rochester, NY, USA: Division of Radiation Chemistry and Toxicology, University
 of Rochester Atomic Energy Project; 1961.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 do not easily cross the blood-brain barrier.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3253456/
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The mercury accumulation mostly in mitochondria and in nucleus was already
 proven years ago.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://sci-hub.se/10.1016/S0027-5107(98)00226-7, 10.1016/0147-6513(85)90012-0,
 10.1002/jat.763, 10.1007/BF00288347
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Inside the cell organic mercury may be demethylated to inorganic mercury.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Suda I, Takahashi H.
 Degradation of methyl and ethyl mercury into inorganic mercury by other
 reactive oxygen species besides hydroxyl radical.
 Archives of Toxicology.
 1992;66(1):34–39.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
tutaj brakuje jakiegoś zdania łaczącego
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It was proven that the Hg(II) ions (a product of demethylation) may inhibit
 the activity of transcription factors that contain zinc fingers, however
 the exact mechanism how Hg(II) disturbs the function of the transcription
 factors is not known, as no data how mercury is coordinated by those transcript
ion factors were provided.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
10.1016/S0006-2952(01)00629-3
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One of the mechanisms of the inhibition of the transcription factors could
 be the formation of the aberrant metal binding site, as Hg(II) in the aqueous
 environment tend to form linear complexes, however the formation of complexes
 with higher coordination number is possible, those complexes usually are
 distorted, with T-shaped geometry of the complex being an extreme example
 of the three-coordinated species.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cytacja
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the living organisms, correspondingly to the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{hsab}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, Hg(II), as a soft Lewis acid will preferentially react with sulfhydryl
 groups (soft Lewis bases), therefore it is not surprising that the cell
 detoxifying mechanisms copiously utilize thiolates to sense (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{merr}
\end_layout

\end_inset

), sequester (e.g.
 metallothioneins), and to enzymatically process mercury compounds 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
10.1021/bi100537f tu jest ciekawy CXXC
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to less toxic forms or to Hg(0).
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fmicb.2021.682605/full
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Marginal
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hg(0) is the major form of mercury emitted to the atmosphere.
 Hg(II) buried in sediments may be reduced to Hg(0), which can be re-emited
 to the astmosphere.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fmicb.2021.682605/full
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the cytoplasm Hg(II) will preferentially form digonsl complexes with
 low molecular weight compounds with thiol groups (i.e.
 cysteine, glutathione), however when Hg(II) interacts the protein, like
 in case of Hg(II)-substituted rubredoxin, the protein may already impose
 a structurally defined metal binding site, where the Hg(II) will adopt
 a tetrahedral or pseudotetrahedral architecture.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
10.1007/pl00010668
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The observed coordination in the crystal structure does not necessarily
 correspond to the Hg(II) binding site formed in the solution, as have been
 verified in case of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{atox}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 – contrarily to the crystal structure (PDB 1FE4, dimer, crystallized at
 pH 6.5) in solution (pH 7.5) Hg(II) prefers to form linear complexes with
 monomeric protein.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
10.1002/chem.201204184
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

