\begin_layout Standard
The described methodology allowed me to estimate the highest known (so far)
 stability of Hg(II) and protein complex, not just any kind of the complex,
 but the first described, pseudotetrahedral Hg(II)-complex formed at the
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{ppi}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, that is formed preferentially at pH 7.4.
 Extremely high Hg(II) affinity towards 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rad}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 causes the replacement of physiologically occurring Zn(II) in the zinc
 hook domain.
 It would be an exaggeration to claim that the replacement of Zn(II) by
 Hg(II) is the sole reason of Hg(II) genotoxicity, especially taking into
 account the fact that the Hg(II)-saturated 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
